TCP vs UDP
🎯 Objective

Learn the differences between TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) and UDP (User Datagram Protocol), understand how they work, their advantages, disadvantages, use cases, and how to inspect network connections using Linux.

📖 What is TCP?

TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) is a connection-oriented transport layer protocol that provides reliable, ordered, and error-checked communication between devices.

Before sending data, TCP establishes a connection between the sender and receiver.

Features of TCP
Connection-oriented
Reliable data delivery
Error detection and recovery
Data arrives in order
Flow control
Congestion control
TCP Three-Way Handshake

Before data transmission, TCP establishes a connection using the Three-Way Handshake.

Client                           Server

  SYN  ------------------------->

       <--------------------- SYN + ACK

  ACK  ------------------------->

After the handshake, data transfer begins.

What is UDP?

UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is a connectionless transport layer protocol.

It sends data without establishing a connection and does not guarantee delivery, ordering, or error recovery.

Features of UDP
Connectionless
Faster than TCP
Low overhead
No delivery guarantee
No retransmission
No congestion control

TCP vs UDP Comparison
| Feature            | TCP                       | UDP                          |
| ------------------ | ------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Connection         | Connection-oriented       | Connectionless               |
| Reliability        | Reliable                  | Best effort                  |
| Data Order         | Guaranteed                | Not guaranteed               |
| Error Recovery     | Yes                       | No                           |
| Speed              | Slower                    | Faster                       |
| Header Size        | 20–60 bytes               | 8 bytes                      |
| Flow Control       | Yes                       | No                           |
| Congestion Control | Yes                       | No                           |
| Acknowledgments    | Required                  | Not required                 |
| Typical Use        | Web, Email, File Transfer | Streaming, Gaming, VoIP, DNS |


How TCP Works
+---------+        +---------+
| Client  |        | Server  |
+---------+        +---------+
      | SYN               |
      |------------------>|
      |<------------------|
      | SYN + ACK         |
      |------------------>|
      | ACK               |
      |==================>|
      |     DATA          |


TCP Applications
Web browsing (HTTP/HTTPS)
Email (SMTP, IMAP, POP3)
File transfer (FTP)
SSH
Database connections

UDP Applications
DNS queries
Video streaming
Voice over IP (VoIP)
Online gaming


Advantages of TCP
Reliable communication
Error checking
Ordered delivery
Suitable for important data
Advantages of UDP
Very fast
Low latency
Small header
Ideal for real-time applications
Disadvantages
TCP
Higher overhead
Slower because of acknowledgments and retransmissions
UDP
No reliability
Packets may be lost or arrive out of order
Linux Commands

Show listening TCP and UDP ports:

ss -tuln

Show only TCP ports:

ss -tl

Show only UDP ports:

ss -ul

List open files and network sockets (if installed):

sudo lsof -i

If lsof is missing:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install lsof



